## Codex Build Prompt: `nfsview` ‚Äî Ratatui demo-style NFS client TUI (with observed connections by IP)

You are an expert Rust engineer specializing in terminal UIs and Linux kernel statistics.

### Goal

Build a production-quality Rust terminal UI (TUI) named **`nfsview`** that displays **real-time Linux NFS client statistics**. The UI and app architecture must be clearly inspired by Ratatui‚Äôs official `examples/apps/demo` app (tabs, table selection, charts/gauges, help footer, event loop, input modes). Users should feel it‚Äôs ‚Äúthe Ratatui demo, but for NFS.‚Äù ([ratatui.rs](https://ratatui.rs/examples/apps/demo/?utm_source=chatgpt.com))

### Scope (MVP)

* **Client-side only. No server-side (`/proc/net/rpc/nfsd`) stats.**
* Support NFSv3, NFSv4.1, NFSv4.2 mounts (detect per mount; show and filter/sort across all).
* Work on kernels **4.18+** (Rocky 8 era) through 6.x.
* Must include **observed TCP connections** for NFS mounts: **which remote IPs are we connected to**, and counts per IP, so we can validate `nconnect` / distribution.

---

## Data Sources (Linux procfs/sysfs only)

### 1) Per-mount NFS client counters + per-op stats

**Primary source:** `/proc/self/mountstats`
Parse NFS mount blocks and extract:

* mount identity: mountpoint, device (server:/export), fstype
* mount options: vers, proto, nconnect, addr=, clientaddr= if present
* per-op counters and timing aggregates used by `nfsiostat`-style reporting
  Be robust to format variations across kernel 4.18‚Äì6.x and NFS versions. Never panic. Produce partial results if needed. ([man7.org](https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/mountstats.8.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com))

### 2) RPC global client stats (optional/secondary display)

**Source:** `/proc/net/rpc/nfs`
Parse client RPC counters and expose as a small panel in Overview / Raw. ([man7.org](https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/nfsstat.8.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com))

### 3) Mount option parsing for nconnect and mapping mounts

**Source:** `/proc/mounts` (fallback `/etc/mtab`)
Extract options including `nconnect=<N>`, `vers=`, `proto=`, `addr=` and map them to mountstats mounts.

### 4) Observed connections by remote IP (required)

We need: for each NFS mount, show the set of remote IPs we are actively connected to, and how many established connections exist to each IP.

Implementation requirement:

* Prefer **socket inode mapping** to associate established TCP sockets with the owning process/namespace and remote endpoint:

  * Parse `/proc/net/tcp` and `/proc/net/tcp6` to find sockets with state `ESTABLISHED` and remote port `2049` (NFS) (and optionally `111` if you later decide; but for MVP stick to `2049`).
  * Each entry contains a socket inode.
  * Walk `/proc/<pid>/fd/*` symlinks (`socket:[inode]`) to find which process holds each inode.
  * For each PID found, map it to a mount‚Äôs NFS ‚Äúuserspace client‚Äù activity **heuristically**:

    * Primary: match remote IP to mount‚Äôs `addr=` (if present) or to resolved IP(s) of the mount‚Äôs server name (see below).
    * Secondary: count all NFS established sockets regardless of process, then bucket them by remote IP; later attribute to mounts by remote IP matching.
* Also implement **server hostname resolution** for mount device like `server:/export`:

  * Try to resolve `server` via `getaddrinfo` at startup and periodically (cache results, refresh every 60s).
  * Use resolved IP set to map observed remote IPs to mounts.
* Do not require root. If `/proc/<pid>/fd` permission blocks inode mapping for other users‚Äô PIDs, gracefully degrade:

  * Still show observed remote IPs from `/proc/net/tcp*` globally for port 2049, but mark attribution confidence lower (show `?`).
* UI must show ‚ÄúObserved connections per remote IP‚Äù for selected mount and total.

Notes:

* This observed approach is kernel-agnostic and works on 4.18+.
* Must support IPv4 and IPv6.
* Must handle multiple mounts to same server IP; attribution can be ‚Äúshared‚Äù but still useful for distribution.

